[We are told that the authorities are unsure if the number of cases of Legionnaires' disease in the Detroit metropolitan area is unusual or if there is any epidemiological link among the cases, which are still under investigation. However, the diagnosis of even a single case of Legionnaires' disease implies the presence of an environmental source to which other susceptible individuals are likely to have been exposed. It is, therefore, a public health imperative to find that source to prevent further cases.

Legionellosis is an infectious disease caused by a Gram-negative bacillus of the genus _Legionella_. Legionnaires' disease is the acute pneumonic form of legionellosis and Pontiac fever is a less severe, non-pneumonic form. Pontiac fever develops from hours to 2 days after initial infection, with fever, malaise and muscle aches, whereas Legionnaires' disease has an incubation period of 2 to 14 days after exposure. Legionnaires' disease, and presumably Pontiac fever, is acquired by inhalation of an infectious dose of aerosolized _Legionella_.

More than 70 percent of cases of Legionnaires' disease are due to _L. pneumophila_ serogroup 1, except in Australia and New Zealand, where _L. pneumophila_ serogroup 1 has accounted for only 45.7 percent of cases of community-acquired legionellosis, and _Legionella longbeachae_ has accounted for 30.4 percent of cases (1). _L. longbeachae_ is found in soil and potting mix (2), and Legionnaires' disease due to _L. longbeachae_ has been associated with the use of potting soil. Unlike _L. longbeachae_, _L. pneumophila_ is found in water sources, such as natural aquatic bodies, including rivers, lakes, and thermally polluted waters.

Water temperatures of 25-40 C (77-104 F) support the highest concentrations of the organism in water storage tanks of plumbing systems. Aerosolization of the contaminated warm water can occur in showers, spa pools, sprays in groceries, fountains, cooling towers, and car washes. If a cooling tower is the implicated source, the effect of wind speed and direction on _Legionella_-contaminated plumes from the cooling tower may influence the distribution of cases.

Legionnaires' disease attacks more frequently and is more severe in individuals who are elderly, smokers, alcoholics, or who have an underlying illness such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), or a weakened immune system as a result of, for example, organ transplant or taking immunosuppressive drugs (such as corticosteroid therapy) for other reasons. However, healthy individuals can also be at risk of contracting this disease.

References:
1. Yu VL, et al: Distribution of _Legionella_ species and serogroups isolated by culture in patients with sporadic community-acquired legionellosis: An international collaborative survey. J Infect Dis. 2002; 186(1): 127-8. Available at http://www.legionella.org/lp_distribution.pdf.

2. Ross IS, Mee BJ, Riley TV: _Legionella longbeachae_ in Western Australian potting mix. Med J Aust 1997; 166(7): 387.

The Detroit metropolitan area, referred to as metro Detroit, is a major metropolitan area located in Southeast Michigan. The urbanized area covers parts of the counties of Macomb, Oakland, and Wayne. Detroit, with a population of 701 475 in 2012 and the seat of government for Wayne County, is the most populous city in the state of Michigan (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Detroit). Wayne County has a population of 1.8 million, excluding that of Detroit. Macomb County borders Wayne County to the northeast and Oakland County to the northwest. For a map showing the location of Detroit within Wayne County and within Michigan, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wayne_County_Michigan_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Detroit_highlighted.svg. - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/2_1t.]
